@paipai880429 Don't know if you ever got your early stopping work complete.  But I've done something similar based on the xGBoost early stopping rounds parameter as well as the evaluation logger example in the mxnet team's documents:

```
mx.callback.early.stop <- function (period, nrounds, logger = NULL, maximize=TRUE, verbose=FALSE) 
{
    function(iteration, nbatch, env) {
        if (nbatch%%period == 0 && !is.null(env$metric)) {
            result <- env$metric$get(env$train.metric)
            if (nbatch != 0) 
                cat(paste0("Batch [", nbatch, "] Train-", result$name, 
                  "=", result$value, "\n"))
            if (!is.null(logger)) {
                if (class(logger) != "mx.metric.logger") {
                  stop("Invalid mx.metric.logger.")
                }
                logger$train <- c(logger$train, result$value)
                if (!is.null(env$eval.metric)) {
                  result <- env$metric$get(env$eval.metric)
                  if (nbatch != 0) 
                    cat(paste0("Batch [", nbatch, "] Validation-", 
                      result$name, "=", result$value, "\n"))
                  logger$eval <- c(logger$eval, result$value)
                      if (iteration > nrounds) {
                        if(maximize) {
                            if(sum(result$value > tail(logger$eval,nrounds)) == 0 ) { 
                                bst.round <- which.max(logger$eval)
                                if (verbose) {
                                    print(paste0("Best round: ", bst.round, "; Best metric: ", max(logger$eval)))
                                    print(paste0("This round: ", result$value))
                                }
                                return(FALSE) 
                            }  
                        } else if(sum(result$value < tail(logger$eval,nrounds)) == 0 ) { 
                                bst.round <- which.min(logger$eval)
                                if (verbose) {
                                    print(paste0("Best round: ", bst.round, "; Best metric: ", min(logger$eval)))
                                    print(paste0("This round: ", result$value))
                                }
                                return(FALSE)                           
                        } 
                    }
                }
            }
        return(TRUE)
        }
    }
}
```

You can call it like so:

```
model <- mx.model.FeedForward.create(lenet, X=train.array, y=train.y,
    num.round=500, array.batch.size=bs,
    learning.rate=lr, momentum=0.9, wd=0.00001,
    eval.metric=mx.metric.logloss,
    epoch.end.callback= mx.callback.early.stop(5,10,logger, maximize=FALSE, verbose=TRUE),
    eval.data=list(data=val.array, label=val.y))
```

It is in fact quite non-trivial to fine tune a pre-trained model whether the model is trained with MXNet or converted from other frameworks. An example is @taoari's https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/pull/1568.

MXNet has a powerful execution engine. But there's a large room to improve the usability of its API. Fine tuning is an example of MXNet's ["underlying architecture bleeding through into the semantic model"](https://cloud.google.com/dataflow/blog/dataflow-beam-and-spark-comparison). It requires significant efforts to redesign the API to stop the bleeding. 

